Grayscale images¶

The simplest possible image is a grayscale image, stored in a matrix, i.e. a rank-2 tensor.

Gray scale images have only one color channel.

This color channel is the grayscale number which runs from 0 (black) to 255 (white)

The gray-scale values can also run from 0 to 1 if the image is normalized.

The following is a very low resolution image of a handwritten digit "5"

SHAPE: (10, 10)

Technically a 2D image is a mathematical function, specifically a scalar field g=g(x,y), where g is the grayscale number and (x,y) represents the position in the image.

i.e. given a position in the matrix (location in image in the x-y plane) return the gray-scale number (scalar)

This can be plotted as a surface with two independent variables (x,y) and one independent response variable z, as shown below.

If you wanted, you could compute the gradient of this function using finite difference in 2 dimensions. (this forms a convolutional filter)

Regions of "steep" gradient correspond to edges. This derivative based method was the origin of many "pre-deep learning" edge detection methods.

In [4]:
#SURFACE PLOT
def surface_plot(image,angle=90):
    # create the x and y coordinate arrays (here we just use pixel indices)
    xx, yy = np.mgrid[0:image.shape[0], 0:image.shape[1]]
    fig = plt.figure()
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
    ax.plot_surface(xx, yy, image[:,:] ,rstride=1, cstride=1, cmap=plt.cm.gray,linewidth=0)
    ax.view_init(elev=angle, azim=0)
    plt.show()

surface_plot(x,50)
surface_plot(x,70)
surface_plot(x,90)

It is common to give the color channel it's own dimension by converting the matrix (rank-2 tensor) to a rank-3 tensor.

The color channels are typically stored in either the last or first dimension of the matrix

  • KERAS (and PIL) CONVENTION --> img.shape=(H,W,C)

  • PYTORCH CONVENTION --> img.shape=(C,H,W)

  • H=the height of the image (number of pixels)
  • W=the width of the image (number of pixels)
  • C=number of color channels

For this lab we will use the Keras convention, next week we will use Py-Torch

# INSERT CODE FOR UTILITY FUNCTION HERE
import numpy as np
def explore_image(image):
    #tensor = torch.from_numpy(image)
    print('TYPE: ', type(image))
    print('SHAPE: ', image.shape)
    print('NUMBER OF PIXELS: ', image.shape[0]*image.shape[1])
    print('NUMBER OF TENSOR ENTRIES: ', image.size)
    if len(image.shape) == 2:
        image = image.reshape(image.shape[0],image.shape[1], 1)
    print('N CHANNELS: ', image.shape[2])
    print('MIN: ', image.min())
    print('MAX: ', image.max())
    print('TYPE: ', image.dtype)
    
    if image.shape[2] == 1:
        plt.imshow(image, cmap=plt.cm.gray)
        plt.show()
    else:
        plt.imshow(image, cmap=plt.cm.rainbow)
        plt.show()

Color images¶

Color images have 3 color channels for the three primary colors (R,G,B)

Therefore they must be stored as rank-3 tensors (i.e. a stack of 3 matrices on top of each other)

Assignment 3.1.3

Write a function filter(x) which applies a convolutional filter to the input image.

Do this "manually" using a triple for loop over (channels, H, W) instead of using np.convolve

Use the following edge detection filter: filter_ED=[[0,-1,0],[-1,4,-1],[0,-1,0]]

Run the convolved image through explore_image

In [16]:
def filter(img, filter_ED):
    #filter_ED=[[0,-1,0],[-1,4,-1],[0,-1,0]]
    filter_ED = np.asarray(filter_ED)
    filter_r = filter_ED.shape[0]
    filter_c = filter_ED.shape[1]
    
    height =  img.shape[0] - filter_ED.shape[0] + 1
    width =  img.shape[1] - filter_ED.shape[1] + 1
    channel = img.shape[2]
    
    Z = np.zeros((height, width, channel))
    
    for c in range(channel):
        for h in range(height):
            for w in range(width):
                new_z = img[h:h+filter_r, w:w+filter_c, c]
                
                Z[h,w,c] = np.sum(np.multiply(new_z, filter_ED))
    return Z

Batches of gray-scale images¶

Often in deep learning we "stack" many images into a "batch" of samples to accelerate vectorized computation.

This increases the tensor rank by 1 dimension

When we load it from Keras it comes in as a "batch" of C=60000 images with resolution 28x28 (i.e H=28 and W=28) of gray-scale images.

In this way we can store the entire dataset in one tensor

  • KERAS (and PIL) CONVENTION --> dataset.shape=(B,H,W,C)

  • PYTORCH CONVENTION --> dataset.shape=(B,C,H,W)

  • B=number of samples (batch dimension)
  • H=the height of the image (number of pixels)
  • W=the width of the image (number of pixels)
  • C=number of color channels

MNIST¶

MNIST is a is a famous deep-learning data-set with hand-written digits

This is a dataset of 60,000 28x28 grayscale images of the 10 digits, along with a test set of 10,000 images. More info can be found at the MNIST homepage.

loaded from Keras as a Tuple of NumPy arrays: (x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test).

x_train: uint8 NumPy array of grayscale image data with shapes (60000, 28, 28), containing the training data. Pixel values range from 0 to 255.

y_train: uint8 NumPy array of digit labels (integers in range 0-9) with shape (60000,) for the training data.

x_test: uint8 NumPy array of grayscale image data with shapes (10000, 28, 28), containing the test data. Pixel values range from 0 to 255.

y_test: uint8 NumPy array of digit labels (integers in range 0-9) with shape (10000,) for the test data.

https://keras.io/api/datasets/mnist/

#INSERT CODE TO CHECK LOAD BALANCE OF THE VARIOUS DIGITS (CLASSES)
def CheckCount(data):
    total = 0
    for i,j in zip(np.unique(data,return_counts=True)[0], np.unique(data,return_counts=True)[1]):
        print(f"label = {i}\tcount = {j}")
        total += j
    print(f'TOTAL = {total}')

Batches of color images¶

CIFAR10 is a famous deep learning data set. It is similar to MNIST but has color images instead of grayscale

This is a dataset of 50,000 32x32 color training images and 10,000 test images, labeled over 10 categories. See more info at the CIFAR homepage.

The classes are:

  • Label Description
  • 0 airplane
  • 1 automobile
  • 2 bird
  • 3 cat
  • 4 deer
  • 5 dog
  • 6 frog
  • 7 horse
  • 8 ship
  • 9 truck

tf.keras.datasets.cifar10.load_data() Loads the CIFAR10 dataset.

This command returns a tuple of NumPy arrays: (x_train, y_train), (x_test, y_test).

x_train: uint8 NumPy array of grayscale image data with shapes (50000, 32, 32, 3), containing the training data. Pixel values range from 0 to 255.

y_train: uint8 NumPy array of labels (integers in range 0-9) with shape (50000, 1) for the training data.

x_test: uint8 NumPy array of grayscale image data with shapes (10000, 32, 32, 3), containing the test data. Pixel values range from 0 to 255.

y_test: uint8 NumPy array of labels (integers in range 0-9) with shape (10000, 1) for the test data.

The following trains an CNN on the MNIST data set

from keras import layers

Build CNN model¶

In [33]:
#-------------------------------------
#BUILD MODEL SEQUENTIALLY (LINEAR STACK)
#-------------------------------------
model = models.Sequential()
model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(28, 28, 1)))
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))

model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu')) 
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))

model.add(layers.Flatten())
model.add(layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

model.summary()

#BUILD MODEL SEQUENTIALLY (LINEAR STACK)
#-------------------------------------
model = models.Sequential()
model.add(layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=(32, 32, 3)))
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))

model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu')) 
model.add(layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)))
model.add(layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'))

model.add(layers.Flatten())
model.add(layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'))
model.add(layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

model.summary()

# Plot training and validation loss

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

loss_values = history_dict['loss']
val_loss_values = history_dict['val_loss']

epochs = range(1, len(loss_values) + 1)


plt.plot(epochs, loss_values, 'bo', label = 'Training loss')
plt.plot(epochs, val_loss_values, 'b', label = 'Validation loss')
plt.title('Training and validation loss')
plt.xlabel('Epochs')
plt.ylabel('Loss')
plt.legend()

plt.show()
